msgid "Te tattha anupakhajja mucchitā bhojanāni bhuñjamānā madaṃ āpajjiṃsu, mattā samānā pamādaṃ āpajjiṃsu, pamattā samānā yathākāmakaraṇīyā ahesuṃ nevāpikassa amusmiṃ nivāpe. "
msgstr " "

msgctxt "mn25:5.14"
msgid "Evañhi te dutiyāpi migajātā na parimucciṃsu nevāpikassa iddhānubhāvā. "
msgstr "failed to get free of the trapper’s power. "

msgctxt "mn25:5.15"
msgid "Yannūna mayaṃ amuṃ nivāpaṃ nivuttaṃ nevāpikassa upanissāya āsayaṃ kappeyyāma. "
msgstr "Why don’t we set up our lair close by the place where the trapper has cast the bait? "

msgctxt "mn25:5.16"
msgid "Tatrāsayaṃ kappetvā amuṃ nivāpaṃ nivuttaṃ nevāpikassa ananupakhajja amucchitā bhojanāni bhuñjissāma, ananupakhajja amucchitā bhojanāni bhuñjamānā na madaṃ āpajjissāma, amattā samānā na pamādaṃ āpajjissāma, appamattā samānā na yathākāmakaraṇīyā bhavissāma nevāpikassa amusmiṃ nivāpe’ti. "
msgstr "Then we can intrude on it and enjoy eating without being reckless. We won’t become indulgent, then we won’t become negligent, and then we won’t be vulnerable to the trapper on account of that bait.’ "

msgctxt "mn25:5.17"
msgid "Te amuṃ nivāpaṃ nivuttaṃ nevāpikassa upanissāya āsayaṃ kappayiṃsu. "
msgstr "And that’s just what they did. "

msgctxt "mn25:5.18"
msgid "Tatrāsayaṃ kappetvā amuṃ nivāpaṃ nivuttaṃ nevāpikassa ananupakhajja amucchitā bhojanāni bhuñjiṃsu, te tattha ananupakhajja amucchitā bhojanāni bhuñjamānā na madaṃ āpajjiṃsu, amattā samānā na pamādaṃ āpajjiṃsu, appamattā samānā na yathākāmakaraṇīyā ahesuṃ nevāpikassa amusmiṃ nivāpe. "
msgstr " "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc6
msgctxt "mn25:5.19"
msgid "Tatra, bhikkhave, nevāpikassa ca nevāpikaparisāya ca etadahosi: "
msgstr "So the trapper and his companions thought, "

# NOTE: I take the unusual construction here as strongly emphatic, with the repeated use of nāma. parajana elsewhere simply means “another person” (Mil 6.3.1) but comm here glosses it as yakkha. A yakkha named Parajana makes an appearance in MN 31. The term literally means “alien”. Presumably it has a sense not dissimilar to “amanussa”.
msgctxt "mn25:5.20"
msgid "‘saṭhāssunāmime tatiyā migajātā ketabino, iddhimantāssunāmime tatiyā migajātā parajanā; "
msgstr "‘Wow, this third herd of deer is so sneaky and devious, they must be some kind of unnatural spirits with psychic power! "

msgctxt "mn25:5.21"
msgid "imañca nāma nivāpaṃ nivuttaṃ paribhuñjanti, na ca nesaṃ jānāma āgatiṃ vā gatiṃ vā. "
msgstr "For they eat the bait we’ve cast without us knowing how they come and go. "

# NOTE: Nyanamoli/BB’s “wicker hurdles” is too clever: vakara/vagura is the same root as wicker. But it’s hardly likely that an entire area was enclosed in wicker. The normal sense is “net”, so presumably it meant nets strung on high stakes. The deer or whatever would have leap over it, thus revealing their position.
#. VAR: daṇḍavākarāhi → daṇḍavāgurāhi (s1-3)
msgctxt "mn25:5.22"
msgid "Yannūna mayaṃ imaṃ nivāpaṃ nivuttaṃ mahatīhi daṇḍavākarāhi samantā sappadesaṃ anuparivāreyyāma, appeva nāma tatiyānaṃ migajātānaṃ āsayaṃ passeyyāma, yattha te gāhaṃ gaccheyyun’ti. "
msgstr "Why don’t we surround the bait on all sides by staking out high nets? Hopefully we might get to see their lair, where they go to hide out.’ "

msgctxt "mn25:5.23"
msgid "Te amuṃ nivāpaṃ nivuttaṃ mahatīhi daṇḍavākarāhi samantā sappadesaṃ anuparivāresuṃ. "
msgstr "And that’s just what they did. "

msgctxt "mn25:5.24"
msgid "Addasaṃsu kho, bhikkhave, nevāpiko ca nevāpikaparisā ca tatiyānaṃ migajātānaṃ āsayaṃ, yattha te gāhaṃ agamaṃsu. "
msgstr "And they saw where the third herd of deer had their lair, where they went to hide out. "

msgctxt "mn25:5.25"
msgid "Evañhi te, bhikkhave, tatiyāpi migajātā na parimucciṃsu nevāpikassa iddhānubhāvā. "
msgstr "And that’s how the third herd failed to get free from the trapper’s power. "

